    <div class="tn-note">
      <strong>&#x1f4dd; Cultural Note:</strong> The king of Assyria is using the question form for emphasis. If a speaker of your language would not use the question form for that purpose, you could translate this as a statement or as an exclamation. Alternate translation: [The kings of Hamath and Arpad and of the cities of Sepharvaim, Hena, and Ivvah are all gone!]
    </div>
    <div class="tn-note">
      <strong>&#x1f4dd; Cultural Note:</strong> If you have decided to translate all of this long quotation in such a way that there will not be quotations within quotations, you can continue doing that in this verse. Alternate translation: [Remind Hezekiah that Assyrians defeated the kings of Hamath and Arpad and of the cities of Sepharvaim, Hena, and Ivvah, so all those kings no longer rule.]
    </div>
    <div class="tn-note">
      <strong>&#x1f4dd; Cultural Note:</strong> In this expression, the words **king** and **city** are singular in form, but they refers to the kings of all three of the cities listed. If it would be helpful in your language, you could use the plural forms in your translation. Alternate translation: [or the kings of the cities of Sepharvaim, Hena, or Ivvah]
